{
  "texts": [
    "However, its requirements have sparked concerns about anti-competitive effects and loss of European tech innovators.The obligations and mechanisms instituted under the DSA are expected to substantially impact major online platforms, which have signed up to previous self-regulatory EU initiatives like the Code of Practice on Disinformation [46] exposed below, but will now face binding statutory duties.",
    "Smaller platformsSmaller platforms are defined in the DSA as those not reaching the threshold of having an active EU user base comprising over 10% of the EU population.These smaller intermediaries will need to implement notice-and-takedown procedures for illegal content in line with Article 14, including accessible reporting channels and timely response mechanisms.",
    "Under Article 15, they must also inform authorities about detected illegal activities on their services.",
    "And all hosting services including smaller platforms are subject to transparency reporting duties on content moderation activities as per Article 13.",
    "For qualifying online platforms, additional obligations apply around implementing internal complaint and redress systems for content moderation disputes under Articles 17 and 18."
  ]
}